A \( k \)-clique is a set \( T \subset S \) where every pair of points in \( T \) are \( k \)-friends, meaning there exists a point \( C \in S \) such that the area of triangle \( ABC \) is \( k \). 1. **Understanding the Area Condition**: - The area of triangle \( ABC \) with vertices \( A(x_1, y_1) \), \( B(x_2, y_2) \), and \( C(x_3, y_3) \) is given by: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \left| x_1(y_2 - y_3) + x_2(y_3 - y_1) + x_3(y_1 - y_2) \right| \] - For this area to be \( k \), the equation simplifies to \( |dx \cdot (y_3 - y_1) - dy \cdot (x_3 - x_1)| = 2k \), where \( dx = x_2 - x_1 \) and \( dy = y_2 - y_1 \). 2. **Key Insight**: - For two points \( A \) and \( B \) to be \( k \)-friends, the greatest common divisor (gcd) of \( dx \) and \( dy \) must divide \( 2k \). 3. **Constructing a \( k \)-Clique**: - Consider a vertical line with integer coordinates. For points on a vertical line, \( dx = 0 \) and \( dy \) is the difference in \( y \)-coordinates. - If the vertical line has a spacing of \( 2k \), then the gcd of \( dx \) and \( dy \) is \( 2k \), which divides \( 2k \). This ensures that any two points on the line are \( k \)-friends. 4. **Verification**: - A vertical line with spacing \( 2k \) contains infinitely many points.
